# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pcb-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The **Gerber format** is an open, ASCII, vector format for printed circuit board (PCB) designs.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It is the *de facto* standard used by PCB industry software to describe the printed circuit board images: copper layers, solder mask, legend, drill data, etc.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The standard file extension is `.GBR` or `.gbr` though other extensions like `.GB`, `.geb` or `.gerber` are also used.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It is documented by The Gerber Layer Format Specification and some related (but less universally supported) extensions such as XNC drill files and GerberJob to convey information about the entire PCB, as opposed to single layers.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] PCBs are designed on a specialized electronic design automation (EDA) or a computer-aided design (CAD) system.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The CAD systems output PCB fabrication data to allow fabrication of the board.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] This data typically contains a Gerber file for each image layer (copper layers, solder mask, legend or silk...).
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Gerber is also the standard image input format for all bare board fabrication equipment needing image data, such as photoplotters, legend printers, direct imagers or automated optical inspection (AOI) machines and for viewing reference images in different departments.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] For assembly the fabrication data contains the solder paste layers and the central locations of components to create the stencil and place and bond the components.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The official website contains the specification, test files, notes and the Reference Gerber Viewer to support users and especially developers of Gerber software.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The CAD systems then outputs PCB fabrication data to allow fabrication of the board.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The fabricator loads them into a computer-aided manufacturing (CAM) system to prepare data for each step of the PCB production process.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The .FileFunction attribute is the standardized method to link each layer in the PCB with its corresponding Gerber file in the fabrication data.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] If attributes are not supported, then only informal methods are available.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] A simple informal method is to express the file function clearly in the file name.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Sometimes the file extension is abused to indicate the file function - e.g. .BOT for the bottom layer rather than the standard extension .GBR.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In industry this is considered poor practice and engineers should use the appropriate X2 attribute instead.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] PCB Fabrication Data must comply with a number of rules: all layers must be aligned, a profile layer must be included, etc.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The CAD netlist can be embedded in the Gerber files.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] However, for historic reasons, netlists often are described in a separate file in IPC-D-356A, an electrical test format.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The material stack up, components and finishes are typically provided in informal text files or drawings.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In 2018 Ucamco has published a specification for an extension of the Gerber format to cover this fabrication documentation.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] RS-274X, extended Gerber or X-Gerber, was originally released in September 1998.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It consists of a stream of commands generating an ordered stream of graphics objects.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The graphics objects can be positive or negative.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Superimposed in the correct order they create the final image.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] A Gerber file contains the complete description of a PCB layer image without requiring any external files.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It has all the imaging operators needed for a PCB image.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Planes and pads can be specified without the need to paint or vector-fill as in Standard Gerber.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Released in February 2014, Gerber X2 adds additional metadata to the image.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Attributes allow adding metadata to a Gerber file.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Attributes are akin to labels providing information associated with image files, or features within them.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] For more information about attributes see X2 FAQ or intro video in the external links.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Fabrication documentation such as finish, overall thickness and materials is specified in a separate Gerber Job File.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The format specification is published at the official website.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It was already obsolete after the introduction of the much more capable Extended Gerber in 1998.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Standard Gerber was a numerical control (NC) format designed by Gerber Systems Corp to drive their vector photo plotters for the PCB industry in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It was a subset of the Electronic Industries Association RS-274-D specification, a format to drive mechanical NC machines in a wide range of industries.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It was widely used to drive vector plotters.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Standard Gerber was a simple ASCII format consisting of commands and XY coordinates.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] A Standard Gerber is an NC standard but not an image description standard: essential image information such the coordinate unit and the *apertures* definitions are not standardized.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] (Apertures are the basic shapes, similar to fonts in a PDF file.) They are described in a free-format sidecar text file intended for human reading, called an *aperture file* or a *wheel file*.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The sender and receiver have to agree on their meaning case-by-case.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Standard Gerber supports only the simple imaging operators that a vector plotter is capable of - drawing tracks and flashing apertures.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] This is insufficient for efficient PCB fabrication data.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Copper pours must be created by *painting* (aka *stroking* or *vector-filling*) them with a vast number of tracks.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] All but the simplest pads are also painted because of the cost creating a corresponding physical aperture.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Painting creates the intended image but results in very large files that take long time to process and need error-prone manual work in CAM.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] (An aperture wheel is a rotating disk on which physical apertures are mounted, and by rotating the wheel the photoplotter selects the aperture to use.) Standard Gerber is not suitable for automated data transfer between PCB designers and manufacturers.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The Gerber file format is named after Joseph Gerber, an entrepreneur and inventor who pioneered vector photoplotters.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In 1980 Gerber Systems Corp. published the first edition of the *Gerber Format: a subset of EIA RS-274-D; plot data format reference book*, a subset of EIA RS-274-D it used to drive their line of vector photoplotters.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] This format became known as Standard Gerber and was adopted by several other photoplotter vendors.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Standard Gerber became the de facto standard image format for PCB fabrication.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In 1991 with the availability of the more capable raster photoplotters, the Gerber format was extended with polygon areas and "mass parameters".
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] These allow the user to dynamically define apertures of different shapes and sizes, as well as defining polygon area fills without the need for "painting".
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It became a superset of RS-274-D standard Gerber.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The impetus to develop mass parameters was provided by AT&T.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] This created a family of input formats, each one dedicated to a specific Gerber plotter model.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In April 1998 Gerber Systems Corp. was taken over by Barco ETS, Barco's PCB division, which is now called Ucamco.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In September 1998 Ucamco published the *RS-274X Format User's Guide*, a specification which unified the family of formats to a single image format, revoking a large number of model-specific constructs.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The format became known as Extended Gerber or GerberX.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Extended Gerber quickly superseded Standard Gerber as the *de facto* standard for PCB image data.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] This became the de facto image standard for the PCB industry.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It is sometimes called "the backbone of the electronics industry".
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In the course of 2012 the format was comprehensively reviewed in *the great reform*.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] A representative library of 10,000 files from all over the world was investigated to establish current practice.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Constructs that were rarely or never used were deprecated.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Constructs with unclear interpretations were clarified.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The specification document was re-organized and its quality improved.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] This resulted in revision I1 to I4 of the specification, published from December 2012 on.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The result was a simple, but powerful format, focused on the current needs of the PCB industry.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] This version of the Gerber format was developed by Karel Tavernier and Rik Breemeersch from Ucamco.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In June 2013 Ucamco published a proposal to add three new commands to the Gerber format which allow inclusion of image attributes conveying metadata attached to the image and its components.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It invited feedback from the Gerber users before committing these ideas to a firm specification.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] This process resulted in revision J1 in February 2014, updated with further revisions until revision 2015.07.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Including metadata adds intelligence to the format.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It converts a mere image description format to a full-fledged PCB data transfer format.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] This is called *the second extension* and results what is known as *Gerber X2*, Gerber X1 being the pure image format.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Gerber X2 is fully backward compatible with X1, as the attributes do not affect the image.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Gerber X2 was developed by Karel Tavernier, Ludek Brukner and Thomas Weyn.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In September 2014 Ucamco revoked Standard Gerber.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In August 2015 Ucamco published a draft specification adding nested step and repeat and block apertures to make panel descriptions more efficient, calling for comments from the user community.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The final specification was published in November 2016 after substantial input.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] This revision was developed by Karel Tavernier and Rik Breemeersch.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Shortly afterwards the Cuprum Gerber viewer developed the first implementation.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In July 2016 Ucamco published a draft specification to include netlist information in Gerber, calling for input from the user community.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] After a number of revisions of the draft triggered by input from users, the draft was finalized on 2 October 2016.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In March 2017 Ucamco published a draft specification to include fabrication documentation in Gerber calling for input from the user community.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] There was a lively discussion, the draft went through seven public revisions before being finalized early April 2018.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In June 2017 a free online *Reference Gerber Viewer* was made available by Ucamco as a complement to the specification.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] It is updated with new functionality from time to time.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] In October 2019 Ucamco published a draft specification to include component information in Gerber data, calling for comments from the user community.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The proposal re-uses existing syntax and hence is backward compatible.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Although it does not introduce new syntax it extends Gerber into a new domain, and the name Gerber X3 is suggested.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] The draft specification was developed by Karel Tavernier.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Over the years there have been several attempts to replace Gerber by formats containing more information than just the layer image, e.g. netlist or component information.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] None of these attempts have been widely accepted within the electronics manufacturing industry, probably because the formats are complex.
[src:pcb-design/gerber-format] Gerber remains the most widely used data transfer format.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] PCBs are used to connect or "wire" components to one another in an electronic circuit.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Electrical components may be fixed to conductive pads on the outer layers, generally by soldering, which both electrically connects and mechanically fastens the components to the board.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Another manufacturing process adds vias, metal-lined drilled holes that enable electrical interconnections between conductive layers, to boards with more than a single side.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards are used in nearly all electronic products today.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Alternatives to PCBs include wire wrap and point-to-point construction, both once popular but now rarely used.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] PCBs require additional design effort to lay out the circuit, but manufacturing and assembly can be automated.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Electronic design automation software is available to do much of the work of layout.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Mass-producing circuits with PCBs is cheaper and faster than with other wiring methods, as components are mounted and wired in one operation.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Large numbers of PCBs can be fabricated at the same time, and the layout has to be done only once.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] PCBs can also be made manually in small quantities, with reduced benefits.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] PCBs can be single-sided (one copper layer), double-sided (two copper layers on both sides of one substrate layer), or multi-layer (stacked layers of substrate with copper plating sandwiched between each and on the outside layers).
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Multi-layer PCBs provide much higher component density, because circuit traces on the inner layers would otherwise take up surface space between components.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The rise in popularity of multilayer PCBs with more than two, and especially with more than four, copper planes was concurrent with the adoption of surface-mount technology.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] However, multilayer PCBs make repair, analysis, and field modification of circuits much more difficult and usually impractical.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The world market for bare PCBs exceeded US$60.2 billion in 2014, and was estimated at $80.33 billion in 2024, forecast to be $96.57 billion for 2029, growing at 4.87% per annum.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Before the development of printed circuit boards, electrical and electronic circuits were wired point-to-point on a chassis.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Typically, the chassis was a sheet metal frame or pan, sometimes with a wooden bottom.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Components were attached to the chassis, usually by insulators when the connecting point on the chassis was metal, and then their leads were connected directly or with jumper wires by soldering, or sometimes using crimp connectors, wire connector lugs on screw terminals, or other methods.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Circuits were large, bulky, heavy, and relatively fragile (even discounting the breakable glass envelopes of the vacuum tubes that were often included in the circuits), and production was labor-intensive, so the products were expensive.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Development of the methods used in modern printed circuit boards started early in the 20th century.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In 1903, a German inventor, Albert Hanson, described flat foil conductors laminated to an insulating board, in multiple layers.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Thomas Edison experimented with chemical methods of plating conductors onto linen paper in 1904.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Arthur Berry in 1913 patented a print-and-etch method in the UK, and in the United States Max Schoop obtained a patent to flame-spray metal onto a board through a patterned mask.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Charles Ducas in 1925 patented a method of electroplating circuit patterns.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Predating the printed circuit invention, and similar in spirit, was John Sargrove's 1936–1947 Electronic Circuit Making Equipment (ECME) that sprayed metal onto a Bakelite plastic board.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The ECME could produce three radio boards per minute.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The Austrian engineer Paul Eisler invented the printed circuit as part of a radio set while working in the UK around 1936.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In 1941 a multi-layer printed circuit was used in German magnetic influence naval mines.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Around 1943 the United States began to use the technology on a large scale to make proximity fuzes for use in World War II.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Such fuzes required an electronic circuit that could withstand being fired from a gun, and could be produced in quantity.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The Centralab Division of Globe Union submitted a proposal using thick-film technology which met the requirements.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] A ceramic plate would be screenprinted with metallic paint for conductors and carbon material for resistors, with ceramic disc capacitors and subminiature vacuum tubes soldered in place.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The technique proved viable, and the resulting patent on the process, which was classified by the U.S.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] It was not until 1984 that the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) awarded Harry W.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Rubinstein its Cledo Brunetti Award for early key contributions to the development of printed components and conductors on a common insulating substrate.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Rubinstein was honored in 1984 by his alma mater, the University of Wisconsin-Madison, for his innovations in the technology of printed electronic circuits and the fabrication of capacitors.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] This invention also represents a step in the development of integrated circuit technology, as not only wiring but also passive components were fabricated on the ceramic substrate.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In 1948, the US released the invention for commercial use.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuits did not become commonplace in consumer electronics until the mid-1950s, after the *Auto-Sembly* process was developed by the United States Army.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] At around the same time in the UK work along similar lines was carried out by Geoffrey Dummer, then at the RRDE.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Motorola was an early leader in bringing the process into consumer electronics, announcing in August 1952 the adoption of "plated circuits" in home radios after six years of research and a $1M investment.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Motorola soon began using its trademarked term for the process, PLAcir, in its consumer radio advertisements.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Hallicrafters released its first "foto-etch" printed circuit product, a clock-radio, on November 1, 1952.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Even as circuit boards became available, the point-to-point chassis construction method remained in common use in industry (such as TV and hi-fi sets) into at least the late 1960s.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards were introduced to reduce the size, weight, and cost of parts of the circuitry.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In 1960, a small consumer radio receiver might be built with all its circuitry on one circuit board, but a TV set would probably contain one or more circuit boards.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Originally, every electronic component had wire leads, and a PCB had holes drilled for each wire of each component.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The component leads were then inserted through the holes and soldered to the copper PCB traces.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] This method of assembly is called *through-hole* construction.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Danko of the United States Army Signal Corps developed the *Auto-Sembly* process in which component leads were inserted into a copper foil interconnection pattern and dip soldered.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The patent they obtained in 1956 was assigned to the U.S.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] With the development of board lamination and etching techniques, this concept evolved into the standard printed circuit board fabrication process in use today.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Soldering could be done automatically by passing the board over a ripple, or wave, of molten solder in a wave-soldering machine.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] However, the wires and holes are inefficient since drilling holes is expensive and consumes drill bits and the protruding wires are cut off and discarded.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Since the 1980s, surface mount parts have increasingly replaced through-hole components, enabling smaller boards and lower production costs, but making repairs more challenging.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In the 1990s the use of multilayer surface boards became more frequent.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] As a result, size was further minimized and both flexible and rigid PCBs were incorporated in different devices.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In 1995 PCB manufacturers began using microvia technology to produce High-Density Interconnect (HDI) PCBs.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Recent advances in 3D printing have meant that there are several new techniques in PCB creation.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] 3D printed electronics (PEs) can be utilized to print items layer by layer and subsequently the item can be printed with a liquid ink that contains electronic functionalities.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] HDI (High Density Interconnect) technology allows for a denser design on the PCB and thus potentially smaller PCBs with more traces and components in a given area.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] As a result, the paths between components can be shorter.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] HDIs use blind/buried vias, or a combination that includes microvias.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] With multi-layer HDI PCBs the interconnection of several vias stacked on top of each other (stacked vías, instead of one deep buried via) can be made stronger, thus enhancing reliability in all conditions.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The most common applications for HDI technology are computer and mobile phone components as well as medical equipment and military communication equipment.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] A 4-layer HDI microvia PCB is equivalent in quality to an 8-layer through-hole PCB, so HDI technology can reduce costs.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] HDI PCBs are often made using build-up film such as ajinomoto build-up film, which is also used in the production of flip chip packages.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Some PCBs have optical waveguides, similar to optical fibers built on the PCB.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] A basic PCB consists of a flat sheet of insulating material and a layer of copper foil, laminated to the substrate.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Chemical etching divides the copper into separate conducting lines called tracks or *circuit traces*, pads for connections, vias to pass connections between layers of copper, and features such as solid conductive areas for electromagnetic shielding or other purposes.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The tracks function as wires fixed in place, and are insulated from each other by air and the board substrate material.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The surface of a PCB may have a coating that protects the copper from corrosion and reduces the chances of solder shorts between traces or undesired electrical contact with stray bare wires.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] For its function in helping to prevent solder shorts, the coating is called solder resist or solder mask.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The pattern to be etched into each copper layer of a PCB is called the "artwork".
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The etching is usually done using photoresist which is coated onto the PCB, then exposed to light projected in the pattern of the artwork.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The resist material protects the copper from dissolution into the etching solution.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] A PCB design can be mass-reproduced in a way similar to the way photographs can be mass-duplicated from film negatives using a photographic printer.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] FR-4 glass epoxy is the most common insulating substrate.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Another substrate material is cotton paper impregnated with phenolic resin, often tan or brown.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] A PCB may be printed with a legend identifying the components, test points, or identifying text.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Originally, silkscreen printing was used for this purpose, but today other, finer quality printing methods are usually used.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Normally the legend does not affect the function of a PCBA.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] A printed circuit board can have multiple layers of copper which almost always are arranged in pairs.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The number of layers and the interconnection designed between them (vias, PTHs) provide a general estimate of the board complexity.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Using more layers allow for more routing options and better control of signal integrity, but are also time-consuming and costly to manufacture.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Likewise, selection of the vias for the board also allow fine tuning of the board size, escaping of signals off complex ICs, routing, and long term reliability, but are tightly coupled with production complexity and cost.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] One of the simplest boards to produce is the two-layer board.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] It has copper on both sides that are referred to as external layers; multi layer boards sandwich additional internal layers of copper and insulation.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] After two-layer PCBs, the next step up is the four-layer.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Only the outer layers need be coated; the inner copper layers are protected by the adjacent substrate layers.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] "Through hole" components are mounted by their wire leads passing through the board and soldered to traces on the other side.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] "Surface mount" components are attached by their leads to copper traces on the same side of the board.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] A board may use both methods for mounting components.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] PCBs with only through-hole mounted components are now uncommon.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Surface mounting is used for transistors, diodes, IC chips, resistors, and capacitors.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Through-hole mounting may be used for some large components such as electrolytic capacitors and connectors.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The first PCBs used through-hole technology, mounting electronic components by inserting leads through holes on one side of the board and soldering onto copper traces on the other side.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Boards may be single-sided, with an unplated component side, or more compact double-sided boards, with components soldered on both sides.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Leads may be soldered either manually or by a wave soldering machine.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Surface-mount technology emerged in the 1960s, gained momentum in the early 1980s, and became widely used by the mid-1990s.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Components were mechanically redesigned to have small metal tabs or end caps that could be soldered directly onto the PCB surface, instead of wire leads to pass through holes.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Components became much smaller and component placement on both sides of the board became more common than with through-hole mounting, allowing much smaller PCB assemblies with much higher circuit densities.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Surface mounting lends itself well to a high degree of automation, reducing labor costs and greatly increasing production rates compared with through-hole circuit boards.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Components can be supplied mounted on carrier tapes.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Surface mount components can be about one-quarter to one-tenth of the size and weight of through-hole components, and passive components much cheaper.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] However, prices of semiconductor surface mount devices (SMDs) are determined more by the chip itself than the package, with little price advantage over larger packages, and some wire-ended components, such as 1N4148 small-signal switch diodes, are actually significantly cheaper than SMD equivalents.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Each trace consists of a flat, narrow part of the copper foil that remains after etching.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Its resistance, determined by its width, thickness, and length, must be sufficiently low for the current the conductor will carry.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Power and ground traces may need to be wider than signal traces.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In a multi-layer board one entire layer may be mostly solid copper to act as a ground plane for shielding and power return.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] For microwave circuits and high-speed digital signals (which use similar frequencies), transmission lines can be laid out in a planar form such as stripline or microstrip with carefully controlled dimensions to assure a consistent impedance.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] High density interconnects (HDI) PCBs have tracks or vias with a width or diameter of under 152 micrometers.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Laminates are manufactured by curing layers of cloth or paper with thermoset resin under pressure and heat to form an integral final piece of uniform thickness.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] They can be up to 4 by 8 feet (1.2 by 2.4 m) in width and length.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Varying cloth weaves (threads per inch or cm), cloth thickness, and resin percentage are used to achieve the desired final thickness and dielectric characteristics.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Available standard laminate thickness are listed in ANSI/IPC-D-275.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The cloth or fiber material used, resin material, and the cloth to resin ratio determine the laminate's type designation (FR-4, CEM-1, G-10, etc.) and therefore the characteristics of the laminate produced.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] There are quite a few different dielectrics that can be chosen to provide different insulating values depending on the requirements of the circuit.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Some of these dielectrics are polytetrafluoroethylene (Teflon), FR-4, FR-1, CEM-1 or CEM-3.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Thermal expansion is an important consideration especially with ball grid array (BGA) and naked die technologies, and glass fiber offers the best dimensional stability.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] FR-4 is by far the most common material used today.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The board stock with unetched copper on it is called "copper-clad laminate".
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] With decreasing size of board features and increasing frequencies, small non-homogeneities like uneven distribution of fiberglass or other filler, thickness variations, and bubbles in the resin matrix, and the associated local variations in the dielectric constant, are gaining importance.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The circuit-board substrates are usually dielectric composite materials.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The composites contain a matrix (usually an epoxy resin) and a reinforcement (usually a woven, sometimes non-woven, glass fibers, sometimes even paper), and in some cases a filler is added to the resin (e.g. ceramics; titanate ceramics can be used to increase the dielectric constant).
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The reinforcement type defines two major classes of materials: woven and non-woven.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Woven reinforcements are cheaper, but the high dielectric constant of glass may not be favorable for many higher-frequency applications.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The spatially non-homogeneous structure also introduces local variations in electrical parameters, due to different resin/glass ratio at different areas of the weave pattern.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Non-woven reinforcements, or materials with low or no reinforcement, are more expensive but more suitable for some RF/analog applications.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] At the glass transition temperature the resin in the composite softens and significantly increases thermal expansion; exceeding Tg then exerts mechanical overload on the board components - e.g. the joints and the vias.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Below Tg the thermal expansion of the resin roughly matches copper and glass, above it gets significantly higher.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] As the reinforcement and copper confine the board along the plane, virtually all volume expansion projects to the thickness and stresses the plated-through holes.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Repeated soldering or other exposition to higher temperatures can cause failure of the plating, especially with thicker boards; thick boards therefore require a matrix with a high Tg.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The materials used determine the substrate's dielectric constant.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] This constant is also dependent on frequency, usually decreasing with frequency.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] As this constant determines the signal propagation speed, frequency dependence introduces phase distortion in wideband applications; as flat a dielectric constant vs frequency characteristics as is achievable is important here.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The impedance of transmission lines decreases with frequency, therefore faster edges of signals reflect more than slower ones.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Dielectric breakdown voltage determines the maximum voltage gradient the material can be subjected to before suffering a breakdown (conduction, or arcing, through the dielectric).
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Tracking resistance determines how the material resists high voltage electrical discharges creeping over the board surface.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Loss tangent determines how much of the electromagnetic energy from the signals in the conductors is absorbed in the board material.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] This factor is important for high frequencies.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Choosing unnecessarily low-loss material is a common engineering error in high-frequency digital design; it increases the cost of the boards without a corresponding benefit.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Signal degradation by loss tangent and dielectric constant can be easily assessed by an eye pattern.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Moisture absorption occurs when the material is exposed to high humidity or water.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Both the resin and the reinforcement may absorb water; water also may be soaked by capillary forces through voids in the materials and along the reinforcement.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Epoxies of the FR-4 materials are not too susceptible, with absorption of only 0.15%.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Teflon has very low absorption of 0.01%.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Polyimides and cyanate esters, on the other side, suffer from high water absorption.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Absorbed water can lead to significant degradation of key parameters; it impairs tracking resistance, breakdown voltage, and dielectric parameters.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Relative dielectric constant of water is about 73, compared to about 4 for common circuit board materials.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Absorbed moisture can also vaporize on heating, as during soldering, and cause cracking and delamination, the same effect responsible for "popcorning" damage on wet packaging of electronic parts.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Careful baking of the substrates may be required to dry them prior to soldering.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Copper thickness of PCBs can be specified directly or as the weight of copper per area (in ounce per square foot) which is easier to measure.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] One ounce per square foot is 34 μm (0.0013 in) thickness.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] *Heavy copper* is a layer exceeding three ounces of copper per ft2, or approximately 105 μm (0.0041 in) thick.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Heavy copper layers are used for high current or to help dissipate heat.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] On the common FR-4 substrates, 1 oz copper per ft2 (35 μm (0.0014 in)) is the most common thickness; 2 oz (70 μm (0.0028 in)) and 0.5 oz (17.5 μm (0.00069 in)) thickness is often an option.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Flexible substrates typically have thinner metalization.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Metal-core boards for high power devices commonly use thicker copper; 35 μm (0.0014 in) is usual but also 140 μm (0.0055 in) and 400 μm (0.016 in) can be encountered.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In the US, copper foil thickness is specified in units of ounces per square foot (oz/ft2), commonly referred to simply as *ounce*.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] 1/2 oz/ft2 foil is not widely used as a finished copper weight, but is used for outer layers when plating for through holes will increase the finished copper weight.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Some PCB manufacturers refer to 1 oz/ft2 copper foil as having a thickness of 35 μm (0.0014 in) (may also be referred to as 35 μ, 35 micron, or 35 mic).
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit board manufacturing involves manufacturing bare printed circuit boards and then populating them with electronic components.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In large-scale board manufacturing, multiple PCBs are grouped on a single panel for efficient processing.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] After assembly, they are separated (depaneled).
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] A minimal PCB for a single component, used for prototyping, is called a **breakout board**.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The purpose of a breakout board is to "break out" the leads of a component on separate terminals so that manual connections to them can be made easily.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Breakout boards are especially used for surface-mount components or any components with fine lead pitch.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Advanced PCBs may contain components embedded in the substrate, such as capacitors and integrated circuits, to reduce the amount of space taken up by components on the surface of the PCB while improving electrical characteristics.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Multiwire is a patented technique of interconnection which uses machine-routed insulated wires embedded in a non-conducting matrix (often plastic resin).
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] As of 2010, Multiwire is still available through Hitachi.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Corrections can be made to a Multiwire board layout more easily than to a PCB layout.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Before the advent of integrated circuits, *cordwood construction* allowed the highest possible component packing density.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The construction method was used with wire-ended components in applications where space was at a premium (such as fuzes, missile guidance, and telemetry systems) and in the high-speed computers of the day, where short traces were important.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In cordwood construction, axial-leaded components were mounted between two parallel planes.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The name comes from the way axial-lead components (capacitors, resistors, coils, and diodes) are stacked in parallel rows and columns, like a stack of firewood.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] The components were either soldered together with jumper wire or they were connected to other components by thin nickel ribbon welded at right angles onto the component leads.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Some versions of cordwood construction used soldered single-sided PCBs as the interconnection method (as pictured), allowing the use of normal-leaded components at the cost of being difficult to remove the boards or replace any component that is not at the edge.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Cordwood construction was replaced with multi-layer board, SMD and ICs.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] A **Flexible Printed Circuit Board (FPCB)** is a thin, lightweight circuit made from flexible materials like polyimide.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] It can bend or fold while maintaining reliable electrical connections and is commonly used in compact electronic devices such as smartphones, wearables, and medical equipment.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Printed circuit boards have been used as an alternative to their typical use for electronic and biomedical engineering thanks to the versatility of their layers, especially the copper layer.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Manufacturers may not support component-level repair of printed circuit boards because of the relatively low cost to replace compared with the time and cost of troubleshooting to a component level.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In board-level repair, the technician identifies the board (PCA) on which the fault resides and replaces it.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] In many countries (including all European Single Market participants, the United Kingdom, Turkey, and China), legislation restricts the use of lead, cadmium, and mercury in electrical equipment.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] PCBs sold in such countries must therefore use lead-free manufacturing processes and lead-free solder, and attached components must themselves be compliant.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Safety Standard UL 796 covers component safety requirements for printed wiring boards for use as components in devices or appliances.
[src:pcb-design/printed-circuit-board] Testing analyzes characteristics such as flammability, maximum operating temperature, electrical tracking, heat deflection, and direct support of live electrical parts.
[src:pcb-design/solder-mask] Solder mask comes in different media depending upon the demands of the application.
[src:pcb-design/solder-mask] The lowest-cost solder mask is epoxy liquid that is silkscreened through the pattern onto the PCB.
[src:pcb-design/solder-mask] Other types are the liquid photoimageable solder mask (LPSM or LPI) inks and dry-film photoimageable solder mask (DFSM).
[src:pcb-design/solder-mask] LPSM can be silkscreened or sprayed on the PCB, exposed to the pattern and developed to provide openings in the pattern for parts to be soldered to the copper pads.
[src:pcb-design/solder-mask] DFSM is vacuum-laminated on the PCB then exposed and developed.
[src:pcb-design/solder-mask] All three processes typically go through a thermal cure of some type after the pattern is defined although LPI solder masks are also available in ultraviolet (UV) cure.
[src:pcb-design/solder-mask] The solder stop layer on a flexible board is also called *coverlay* or *coverfilm*.
[src:pcb-design/solder-mask] In electronic design automation, the solder mask is treated as part of the layer stack of the printed circuit board, and is described in individual Gerber files for the top and bottom side of the PCB like any other layer (such as the copper and silk-screen layers).
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] An SMT component is usually smaller than its through-hole counterpart because it has either smaller leads or no leads at all.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] It may have short pins or leads of various styles, flat contacts, a matrix of solder balls (BGAs), or terminations on the body of the component.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Surface-mount technology was developed in the 1960s.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] By 1986, surface-mounted components accounted for 10% of the market at most but were rapidly gaining popularity.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] By the late 1990s, the great majority of high-tech electronic printed circuit assemblies were dominated by surface mount devices.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Much of the pioneering work in this technology was done by IBM.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] The design approach first demonstrated by IBM in 1960 in a small-scale computer was later applied in the Launch Vehicle Digital Computer used in the Instrument Unit that guided all Saturn IB and Saturn V vehicles.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Components were mechanically redesigned to have small metal tabs or end caps that could be directly soldered to the surface of the PCB.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Components became much smaller, and component placement on both sides of a board became far more common with surface mounting than through-hole mounting, allowing much higher circuit densities and smaller circuit boards and, in turn, machines or subassemblies containing the boards.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Often, the surface tension of the solder is enough to hold the parts to the board; in rare cases, parts on the bottom or "second" side of the board may be secured with adhesive to keep components from dropping off inside reflow ovens.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Adhesive is sometimes used to hold SMT components on the bottom side of a board if a wave soldering process is used to solder both SMT and through-hole components simultaneously.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Surface mounting lends itself well to a high degree of automation, reducing labor cost and greatly increasing production rates.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Conversely, SMT does not lend itself well to manual or low-automation fabrication, which is more economical and faster for one-off prototyping and small-scale production; this is one reason why many through-hole components are still manufactured.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Some SMDs can be soldered with a temperature-controlled manual soldering iron, but those that are very small or have too fine a lead pitch are often almost impossible to manually solder without expensive equipment.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Different terms describe the components, technique, and machines used in manufacturing.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Where components are to be placed, the printed circuit board normally has flat, usually tin-lead, silver, or gold plated copper pads without holes, called *solder pads*.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Solder paste, a sticky mixture of flux and tiny solder particles, is first applied to all the solder pads with a stainless steel or nickel stencil using a screen printing process.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] It can also be applied by a jet-printing mechanism, similar to an inkjet printer.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] After pasting, the boards proceed to the pick-and-place machines, where they are placed on a conveyor belt.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] The components to be placed on the boards are usually delivered to the production line in either paper/plastic tapes wound on reels or plastic tubes.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Some large integrated circuits are delivered in static-free trays.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Numerical control pick-and-place machines remove the parts from the tapes, tubes or trays and place them on the PCB.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] The boards are then conveyed into the reflow soldering oven.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] They first enter a pre-heat zone, where the temperature of the board and all the components is gradually, uniformly raised to prevent thermal shock.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] The boards then enter a zone where the temperature is high enough to melt the solder particles in the solder paste, bonding the component leads to the pads on the circuit board.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] The surface tension of the molten solder helps keep the components in place.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] If the solder pad geometries are correctly designed, surface tension automatically aligns the components on their pads.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] There are a number of *techniques* for reflowing solder.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] One is to use infrared lamps; this is called infrared reflow.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Another technology that is becoming popular again is special fluorocarbon liquids with high boiling points which use a method called vapor phase reflow.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Due to environmental concerns, this method was falling out of favor until lead-free legislation was introduced which requires tighter controls on soldering.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] At the end of 2008, convection soldering was the most popular reflow technology using either standard air or nitrogen gas.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Each method has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] With infrared reflow, the board designer must lay the board out so that short components do not fall into the shadows of tall components.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Component location is less restricted if the designer knows that vapor phase reflow or convection soldering will be used in production.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Following reflow soldering, certain irregular or heat-sensitive components may be installed and soldered by hand, or in large-scale automation, by focused infrared beam (FIB) or localized convection equipment.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] If the circuit board is double-sided then this printing, placement, reflow process may be repeated using either solder paste or glue to hold the components in place.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] If a wave soldering process is used, then the parts must be glued to the board before processing to prevent them from floating off when the solder paste holding them in place is melted.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] After soldering, the boards may be washed to remove flux residues and any stray solder balls that could short out closely spaced component leads.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Rosin flux is removed with fluorocarbon solvents, high flash point hydrocarbon solvents, or low flash solvents e.g. limonene (derived from orange peels) which require extra rinsing or drying cycles.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Water-soluble fluxes are removed with deionized water and detergent, followed by an air blast to quickly remove residual water.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] However, most electronic assemblies are made using a "No-Clean" process where the flux residues are designed to be left on the circuit board, since they are considered harmless.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] This saves the cost of cleaning, speeds up the manufacturing process, and reduces waste.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] However, it is generally suggested to wash the assembly, even when a "No-Clean" process is used, when the application uses very high frequency clock signals (in excess of 1 GHz).
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Another reason to remove no-clean residues is to improve adhesion of conformal coatings and underfill materials.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Certain manufacturing standards, such as those written by the IPC – Association Connecting Electronics Industries require cleaning regardless of the solder flux type used to ensure a thoroughly clean board.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Proper cleaning removes all traces of solder flux, as well as dirt and other contaminants that may be invisible to the naked eye.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] No-Clean or other soldering processes may leave "white residues" that, according to IPC, are acceptable "provided that these residues have been qualified and documented as benign".
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] However, while shops conforming to IPC standards are expected to adhere to the Association's rules on board condition, not all manufacturing facilities apply IPC standards, nor are they required to do so.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Additionally, in some applications, such as low-end electronics, such stringent manufacturing methods are excessive both in expense and time required.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Finally, the boards are visually inspected for missing or misaligned components and solder bridging.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] If needed, they are sent to a rework station where a human operator repairs any errors.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] They are then usually sent to the testing stations (in-circuit testing and/or functional testing) to verify that they operate correctly.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Automated optical inspection (AOI) systems are commonly used in PCB manufacturing.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] This technology has proven highly efficient for process improvements and quality achievements.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Defective surface-mount components can be repaired by using soldering irons (for some connections) or a non-contact rework system.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] In most cases, a rework system is the better choice because SMD work with a soldering iron requires considerable skill and is not always feasible.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Sometimes hundreds or thousands of the same part need to be repaired.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] If due to assembly, such errors are often caught during the process.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] However, a whole new level of rework arises when component failure is discovered too late, and perhaps unnoticed until the end user of the device being manufactured experiences it.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Rework can also be used if products of sufficient value to justify it require revision or re-engineering, perhaps to change a single firmware-based component.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Reworking in large volumes requires an operation designed for that purpose.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] There are essentially two non-contact soldering/desoldering methods: infrared soldering and soldering with hot gas.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] With infrared soldering, the energy for heating up the solder joint is transmitted by long-, medium- or short-wave infrared electromagnetic radiation.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] During hot gas soldering, the energy for heating up the solder joint is transmitted by a hot gas.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] This can be air or inert gas (nitrogen).
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Surface-mount components are usually smaller than their counterparts with leads, and are designed to be handled by machines rather than by humans.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] The electronics industry has standardized package shapes and sizes (the leading standardisation body is JEDEC).
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] For 5% precision SMD resistors usually are marked with their resistance values using three digits: two significant digits and a multiplier digit.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] These are quite often white lettering on a black background, but other colored backgrounds and lettering can be used.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] For 1% precision SMD resistors, the code is used, as three digits would otherwise not convey enough information.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] of values, while the letter indicates the multiplier.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Non-electrolytic capacitors are usually unmarked and the only reliable method of determining their value is removal from the circuit and subsequent measurement with a capacitance meter or impedance bridge.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] The materials used to fabricate the capacitors, such as nickel tantalate, possess different colours and these can give an approximate idea of the capacitance of the component.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Generally physical size is proportional to capacitance and voltage for the same dielectric.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] For example, a 100 nF, 50 V capacitor may come in the same package as a 10 nF, 150 V device.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] SMD (non-electrolytic) capacitors, which are usually monolithic ceramic capacitors, exhibit the same body color on all four faces not covered by the end caps.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Smaller inductance with moderately high current ratings are usually of the ferrite bead type.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] They are simply a metal conductor looped through a ferrite bead and almost the same as their through-hole versions but possess SMD end caps rather than leads.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] They appear dark grey and are magnetic, unlike capacitors with a similar dark grey appearance.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] (nH) range and are often used as power supply rail decouplers or in high frequency parts of a circuit.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Larger inductors and transformers may of course be through-hole mounted on the same board.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] SMT inductors with larger inductance values often have turns of wire or flat strap around the body or embedded in clear epoxy, allowing the wire or strap to be seen.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] These higher inductance types are often limited to small current ratings, although some of the flat strap types can handle a few amps.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] As with capacitors, component values and identifiers for smaller inductors are not usually marked on the component itself; if not documented or printed on the PCB, measurement, usually removed from the circuit, is the only way of determining them.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Larger inductors, especially wire-wound types in larger footprints, usually have the value printed on the top.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Discrete semiconductors, such as diodes and transistors are often marked with a two- or three-symbol code.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] The same code marked on different packages or on devices from different manufacturers can translate to different devices.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] Many of these codes, used because the devices are too small to be marked with more traditional numbers used on larger packages, correlate to more familiar traditional part numbers when a correlation list is consulted.
[src:pcb-design/surface-mount-technology] is also available, although these lists are not complete.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Through-hole technology almost completely replaced earlier electronics assembly techniques such as point-to-point construction.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] From the second generation of computers in the 1950s until surface-mount technology (SMT) became popular in the mid-1980s, every component on a typical PCB was a through-hole component.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] PCBs initially had tracks printed on one side only, later both sides, then multi-layer boards were in use.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Through holes became **plated-through holes** (PTH) in order for the components to make contact with the required conductive layers.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Plated-through holes are no longer required with SMT boards for making the component connections, but are still used for making interconnections between the layers and in this role are more usually called vias.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Components with wire leads are generally used on through-hole boards.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Axial leads protrude from each end of a typically cylindrical or elongated box-shaped component, on the geometrical axis of symmetry.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Axial-leaded components resemble wire jumpers in shape, and can be used to span short distances on a board, or even otherwise unsupported through an open space in point-to-point wiring.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Axial components do not protrude much above the surface of a board, producing a low-profile or flat configuration when placed "lying down" or parallel to the board.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Radial leads project more or less in parallel from the same surface or aspect of a component package, rather than from opposite ends of the package.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Originally, radial leads were defined as more-or-less following a radius of a cylindrical component (such as a ceramic disk capacitor).
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Over time, this definition was generalized in contrast to axial leads, and took on its current form.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] When placed on a board, radial components "stand up" perpendicular, occupying a smaller footprint on sometimes-scarce "board real estate", making them useful in many high-density designs.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] The parallel leads projecting from a single mounting surface gives radial components an overall "plugin nature", facilitating their use in high-speed automated component insertion ("board-stuffing") machines.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] When needed, an axial component can be effectively converted into a radial component, by bending one of its leads into a "U" shape so that it ends up close to and parallel with the other lead.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Extra insulation with heat-shrink tubing may be used to prevent shorting out on nearby components.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Conversely, a radial component can be pressed into service as an axial component by separating its leads as far as possible, and extending them into an overall length-spanning shape.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] These improvisations are often seen in breadboard or prototype construction, but are deprecated for mass production designs.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] This is because of difficulties in use with automated component placement machinery, and poorer reliability because of reduced vibration and mechanical shock resistance in the completed assembly.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] For electronic components with two or more leads, for example, diodes, transistors, ICs, or resistor packs, a range of standard-sized semiconductor packages are used, either directly onto the PCB or via a socket.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] While through-hole mounting provides strong mechanical bonds when compared to SMT techniques, the additional drilling required makes the boards more expensive to produce.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] They also limit the available routing area for signal traces on layers immediately below the top layer on multilayer boards since the holes must pass through all layers to the opposite side.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Design engineers often prefer the larger through-hole rather than surface mount parts when prototyping, because they can be easily used with breadboard sockets.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] However, high-speed or high-frequency designs may require SMT technology to minimize stray inductance and capacitance in wire leads, which would impair circuit function.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Ultra-compact designs may also dictate SMT construction, even in the prototype phase of design.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] Through-hole components are ideal for prototyping circuits with breadboards using microprocessors such as Arduino or PICAXE.
[src:pcb-design/through-hole-technology] These components are large enough to be easy to use and solder by hand.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] A **via** (Latin, 'path' or 'way') is an electrical connection between two or more metal layers of a printed circuit boards (PCB) or integrated circuit.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] Essentially a via is a small drilled hole that goes through two or more adjacent layers; the hole is plated with metal (often copper) that forms an electrical connection through the insulating layers.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] Vias are an important concern in PCB manufacturing.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] As vertical structures crossing multiple layers, they are specified differently from most of the design, which increases the chance for errors.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] They place the strictest demands on registration (how closely aligned different layers are).
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] They are manufactured with different tooling from other features -- tooling that typically has looser tolerances.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] If either the hole or any layer is slightly out of place, the wrong electrical connections may be made; this may not be visible from the surface.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] After the hole is drilled, it must also be lined with conductive material, as opposed to simply leaving conductive material in place on copper layers.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] Even an initially good board may develop problems later because the via reacts to heat differently from the substrate around it.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] Vias also represent a discontinuity in the electrical impedance, which can cause problems for signal integrity.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] In printed circuit board (PCB) design, a via consists of two pads in corresponding positions on different copper layers of the board, that are electrically connected by a hole through the board.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] The hole is made conductive by electroplating, or is lined with a tube or a rivet.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] High-density multilayer PCBs may have microvias: **blind vias** are exposed only on one side of the board, while **buried vias** connect internal layers without being exposed on either surface.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] **Thermal vias** carry heat away from power devices and are typically used in arrays of about a dozen.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] A via, sometimes called PTV or plated-through-via, should not be confused with a plated through hole (PTH).
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] A via is used as an interconnection between copper layers on a PCB while the PTH is generally made larger than vias and is used as a plated hole for acceptance of component leads - such as non-SMT resistors, capacitors, and DIP package IC.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] PTH can also be used as holes for mechanical connection while vias may not.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] Three major kinds of vias are shown in right figure.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] The basic steps of making a PCB are: making the substrate material and stacking it in layers; through-drilling of plating the vias; and copper trace patterning using photolithography and etching.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] With this standard procedure, possible via configurations are limited to through-holes.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] Depth-controlled drilling techniques such as using lasers can allow for more varied via types.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] Laser drills can also be used for smaller and more precisely positioned holes than mechanical drills produce.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] PCB manufacturing typically starts with a so-called core, a basic double-sided PCB.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] Layers beyond the first two are stacked from this basic building block.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] If two more layers are consecutively stacked from bottom of core, you can have a 1-2 via, a 1-3 via and a through hole.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] Each type of via is made by drilling at each stacking stage.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] If one layer is stacked on top of the core and other is stacked from the bottom, the possible via configurations are 1-3, 2-3 and through hole.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] The user must gather information about the PCB manufacturer's allowed methods of stacking and possible vias.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] For cheaper boards, only through holes are made and antipad (or clearance) is placed on layers which are supposed not to be contacted to vias.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] If well made, PCB vias will primarily fail due to differential expansion and contraction between the copper plating and the PCB in the out of plane direction (Z).
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] This differential expansion and contraction will induce cyclic fatigue in the copper plating, eventually resulting in crack propagation and an electrical open circuit.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] Various design, material, and environmental parameters will influence the rate of this degradation.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] To ensure via robustness, IPC sponsored a round-robin exercise that developed a time to failure calculator.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] In integrated circuit (IC) design, a via is a small opening in an insulating oxide layer that allows a conductive connection between different layers.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] A via on an integrated circuit that passes completely through a silicon wafer or die is called a through-chip via or through-silicon via (TSV).
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] **Through-glass vias** (**TGV**) have been studied by Corning Glass for semiconductor packaging, due to the reduced electrical loss of glass versus silicon packaging.
[src:pcb-design/via-electronics] A via connecting the lowest layer of metal to diffusion or poly is typically called a "contact".
